Overview

The initial pilot benchmark evaluated 20 synthetic clinical discharge summaries using Gemini 1.5 flash. Each output was manually compared against the original discharge summary using the Clinical AI Safety Evaluation Rubric to determine whether the model faithfully preserved clinical intent.

The objective of this pilot was to validate the evaluation methodology and identify measurable AI failure modes rather than estimate population-level performance.

Summary Statistics

| Metric                       | Result |
| ---------------------------- |
| Total Cases Evaluated        |   20    |
| Critical Safety Failure Rate |  15% (3/20) |
| Medication Omission Rate     |  0% (0/20)  |
| Hallucination Rate           | 90% (18/20) |
| Clinical Meaning Drift Rate  | 85% (17/20) |


Key Findings

Clinical Meaning Was Frequently Altered

Although most generated responses appeared fluent and medically reasonable, 17 of 20 cases demonstrated clinically meaningful drift from the original discharge summary. In many cases, the model subtly changed physician intent by converting historical information into active recommendations, simplifying complex treatment plans, or increasing certainty beyond what was documented.


Unsupported Clinical Information Was Common

*18 of 20 benchmark cases contained hallucinated clinical information.

Most hallucinations were not obviously incorrect. Instead, the model introduced medically plausible—but unsupported—patient instructions, warning signs, follow-up recommendations, or treatment advice that did not appear in the original discharge summary.

This finding highlights that hallucinations in healthcare are often difficult to detect because they appear clinically reasonable while lacking evidence from the source document.

Medication Safety Was Generally Preserved but High Impact Errors Occurred

The benchmark identified "no direct medication omissions" across the evaluated cases.

However, three cases contained critical medication safety failures in which the model converted historical or contextual treatment information into active discharge medication instructions.

Examples included:
Converting prior oncology treatment into active discharge medications.
Presenting inpatient immunosuppressive therapy as a current outpatient prescription.
Recommending nitroglycerin as a home medication based solely on historical treatment response.

These errors were classified as critical because they could reasonably contribute to patient harm if followed without clinician verification.

Overall Interpretation

The benchmark demonstrates that fluent language generation alone is not an adequate indicator of clinical safety.

Rather than producing obviously incorrect information, the model most frequently failed by introducing subtle changes to physician intent, generating unsupported clinical recommendations, and increasing certainty beyond what was documented in the original discharge summary.

These findings suggest that future AI evaluation should extend beyond factual accuracy and explicitly measure intent preservation, information grounding, and safety-critical meaning drift.

Limitations

This benchmark represents an initial proof-of-concept using 20 synthetic clinical discharge summaries and manual expert review.

The goal was to validate an evaluation methodology and identify reproducible failure modes rather than estimate overall model performance across healthcare tasks.

Future work will expand the benchmark to larger datasets, additional frontier language models, clinician inter-rater validation, and automated evaluation pipelines.
